  "opinion": "As a 73-year-old Italian carpenter living in Bari, I've spent most of my life building things with my hands—wood, frames, structures—so I've always valued the physicality of creation. Social media, for me, is a place where I go to share photos of my garden, my woodworking projects, and the quiet moments of classical music I enjoy. But lately, I've noticed a troubling trend: fake content. It’s not like the old days when you could trust what you saw in the newspaper or the radio. Now, everything feels a bit like a puzzle with too many pieces. I’ve learned to be careful. First, I don’t click on links that seem too good to be true—like those viral posts about easy money or health hacks that don’t make sense. Second, I check the source. If it’s a personal account with a few followers, I ask myself: Is this someone I know? Do they have a history of sharing reliable information? Third, I’ve started to use the 'report' feature on platforms like Facebook and Instagram. It’s a small step, but it helps me keep my feed clean. I also talk to my neighbors and friends in Bari—they’ve been helpful in spotting when something seems off. My creativity helps me see the world in a different way: I don’t just take things at face value. I look for the story behind the image, the context, the details that make it real. And since I’m low on extraversion, I don’t get too caught up in arguments online. I prefer to stay calm and thoughtful, like my woodworking: slow, deliberate, and precise. The key is to remember that trust is built over time, just like a good piece of wood needs time to dry and strengthen.",
